item.description:
chmod is not enough, sometimes. Therefore, we need to adapt our access control lust (see what I did there ?) for our www-data user.
This may or may not be the best solution, but here is a bash script to put in bin/ that does the job :
#!/bin/sh  DIR=&#34;$( cd &#34;$( dirname &#34;$0&#34; )&#34; &amp;&amp; pwd )&#34; cd $DIR # bin/, sibling of app/ cd .. # project root sudo setfacl -R -m u:www-data:rwx -m u:`whoami`:rwx app/cache app/logs sudo setfacl -dR -m u:www-data:rwx -m u:`whoami`:rwx app/cache app/logs sudo setfacl -R -m u:www-data:rwx -m u:`whoami`:rwx web sudo setfacl -dR -m u:www-data:rwx -m u:`whoami`:rwx web
